Wednesday 4/24/13. Discussion of the formula for circumference of a hyperbolic circle (in particular the circumference grows exponentially as the radius increases (!), relation to notion of curvature in differential geometry). The area of a hyperbolic circle of radius R equals 4 pi (sinh(R/2))<sup>2</sup>. Geometric classification of hyperbolic isometries. Review of geometric classification of isometries of R<sup>2</sup>. Recap of examples of hyperbolic isometries (upper half plane model): 
(1) reflection in a hyperbolic line, (2) hyperbolic rotation about a point, (3) translation f(z)=z+b, b in R, and (4) scaling g(z)=az, a in R, a > 0. 
