Wednesday 3/6/13. Completion of proof from Monday. Two quaternions q<sub>1</sub>, q<sub>2</sub> define the same rotation iff q<sub>2</sub>=q<sub>1</sub> or q<sub>2</sub>=-q<sub>1</sub>. The group G of rotations fixing the  origin in R<sup>2</sup> can be identified with the group of unit complex numbers, which is geometrically the circle S<sup>1</sup> of radius 1 and center the origin in R<sup>2</sup>. The group G of rotations fixing the origin in R<sup>3</sup> can be identified with the group of unit quaternions q modulo the equivalence relation given by identifying q and -q. The group of unit quaternions is geometrically the 3-sphere S<sup>3</sup> of radius 1 and center the origin in R<sup>4</sup>. In particular the circle and the 3-sphere can be given the structure of a group (such that the group operation is continuous). This is impossible for spheres in other dimensions. Explanation for the 2-sphere S<sup>2</sup> in R<sup>3</sup> using the ``hairy ball theorem''.
