Monday 2/25/13. Direct and opposite isometries. An isometry T(x)=Ax+b of R<sup>n</sup> is called direct if det(A)=1 and opposite in det(A)=-1. An isometry of R<sup>2</sup> is direct if it preserves the sense (clockwise or counterclockwise) of an angle. An isometry of R<sup>3</sup> is direct if it preserves the notion of right handedness for a triple of vectors. An isometry is direct if it can be obtained by a "continuous process" (made precise mathematically).
